1
00:00:02,916 --> 00:00:14,398
Last night, we spoke of the spiritual faculties, which are the strengths that develop from our spiritual practice and which help us combat difficulties in formal meditation and daily life.

2
00:00:15,461 --> 00:00:21,853
The teaching known as The Raft is related to this theme, and that's what I'd like to talk about tonight.

3
00:00:24,094 --> 00:00:34,649
While the spiritual faculties help us reflect on and value the strengths we're building up, the teaching on the raft suggests how to put these to work in tricky situations.

4
00:00:35,551 --> 00:00:36,972
So it's a different perspective.

5
00:00:37,993 --> 00:00:43,621
In fact, all the Buddha's teachings are saying the same thing from slightly different perspectives.

6
00:00:44,277 --> 00:00:55,755
This one tackles the dynamic and powerful challenges we come across in life and gives us a vivid and quite undignified image for how we might somehow scrabble our way through.

7
00:00:57,777 --> 00:01:05,269
The Sutta describes someone following a path that leads to a shore that is perilous and risky, owing to a great flood of water.

8
00:01:06,371 --> 00:01:11,060
Across the water he sees another shore where the ground is safe and secure.

9
00:01:12,182 --> 00:01:16,629
The Buddha then says, The thought would occur to him,

10
00:01:17,790 --> 00:01:33,054
What if I were to gather grass, twigs, branches and leaves, and having bound them together to make a raft, were to cross over to safety on the other shore, independence on the raft, making an effort with my hands and feet?

11
00:01:34,695 --> 00:01:37,460
So he builds the raft and makes it to the other shore.

12
00:01:38,721 --> 00:01:41,387
Then there is the question of what to do with the raft.

13
00:01:42,468 --> 00:01:47,055
He's tempted to take it with him, but according to the Buddha, that's a mistake.

14
00:01:48,183 --> 00:01:58,417
After pondering the question for a while, he has the thought, why don't I, having dragged it on dry land or sinking it in the water, go wherever I like?

15
00:01:59,397 --> 00:02:02,201
That, according to the Buddha, is the right decision.

16
00:02:04,564 --> 00:02:07,549
In another Sutta, the various symbols are explained.

17
00:02:08,569 --> 00:02:12,275
The great expanse of water stands for the fourfold flood.

18
00:02:13,396 --> 00:02:16,401
The raft stands for the noble eightfold path.

19
00:02:17,544 --> 00:02:24,480
The near shore stands for self-identity while the far shore stands for unbinding.

20
00:02:26,967 --> 00:02:32,280
Identifying with our normal limited sense of self is our problem on the near shore.

21
00:02:34,014 --> 00:02:43,825
When we believe we're confined within our body and mind, and expressed by a personality and described in our life story, then we're on perilous ground.

22
00:02:45,046 --> 00:02:47,509
At any moment our body can fall ill or die.

23
00:02:47,569 --> 00:02:56,580
Our personality can let us down when we get a shock or get depressed, and can wither away altogether through Alzheimer's or other diseases.

24
00:02:57,437 --> 00:03:04,408
We might suffer some calamity which makes a mockery of all we achieved and so our personal story becomes one of failure.

25
00:03:06,231 --> 00:03:13,562
On the far shore we know we are not confined within our body, mind, personality or life history.

26
00:03:14,685 --> 00:03:21,235
So we can look on our physical, mental or social troubles with tender compassion but without distress.

27
00:03:23,391 --> 00:03:26,716
The ultimate unbinding happens when we're fully enlightened.

28
00:03:27,837 --> 00:03:39,514
But for the moment, we can think of the far shore as those temporary periods of ease in our practice, when we've worked our way through some hindrance and are now at ease.

29
00:03:42,837 --> 00:03:48,605
To get to the far shore, we have to cross the expanse of water, the fourfold flood.

30
00:03:49,430 --> 00:03:54,675
In essence, these are the hindrances again, but from a different perspective.

31
00:03:54,695 --> 00:04:05,169
The hindrances describe the energetic manifestation of our troubles, without reference to any background story that may be prompting desire, aversion, restlessness, etc.

32
00:04:06,890 --> 00:04:13,158
This is an especially useful way to view these in meditation, where we're looking at moment-to-moment experience.

33
00:04:14,151 --> 00:04:23,204
The floods describe these same troubles but in broader terms rather than momentary energies.

34
00:04:24,625 --> 00:04:28,511
They describe what we identify with in life.

35
00:04:30,132 --> 00:04:31,134
I'll do that last bit again.

36
00:04:32,156 --> 00:04:37,762
The floods describe these same troubles but in broader terms rather than momentary energies.

37
00:04:38,925 --> 00:04:42,048
They describe what we identify with in life.

38
00:04:44,982 --> 00:04:54,853
Thus, the floods are related to the Kanda, and the first flood, termed the flood of sensuality, overlaps with the first Kanda, termed the body.

39
00:04:56,196 --> 00:05:06,067
The Kanda describe our identities in terms that encourage us to tease things out at the deep level we can sometimes achieve within the steady focus of a Pasana.

40
00:05:07,369 --> 00:05:11,074
It's often termed a deconstruction of our sense of self.

41
00:05:11,932 --> 00:05:18,459
This microscopic focus is powerful, but can seem puzzling or academic from our normal perspective.

42
00:05:19,622 --> 00:05:32,437
In order to facilitate our practice at times when we don't have so much calm objectivity, we have the image of a fourfold flood as a way to tease out the problems that come from identifying with aspects of our life.

43
00:05:34,408 --> 00:05:39,694
The first three are the floods of sensuality, becoming and views.

44
00:05:40,855 --> 00:05:45,459
Underlying these three, we have the fourth one, the flood of ignorance.

45
00:05:48,322 --> 00:06:04,399
We get swept away by the flood of sensuality whenever we indulge sense pleasure mindlessly, whether it be for food, sex, music, material goods, intoxicants, whatever the material world can offer by way of pleasure and escapism.

46
00:06:05,627 --> 00:06:10,697
This flood also drowns us when we are upset by the unattractive nature of the material world.

47
00:06:11,338 --> 00:06:20,295
Hunger, thirst and physical pain are our primary fears here, but we also deplore noise, ugliness, stinks and so on.

48
00:06:22,586 --> 00:06:25,071
We might not think of ourselves as sensual.

49
00:06:25,591 --> 00:06:37,848
Perhaps we're more cerebral, easily absorbed by computers or books or abstract ideas, but not very interested in food or music or sex or whether the house is painted red or green or what the wallpaper looks like.

50
00:06:39,370 --> 00:06:43,297
Thus, we might think that sensuality is one flood we don't have to worry about.

51
00:06:45,019 --> 00:06:50,687
But our cerebral function depends on being warm and healthy and having food to eat.

52
00:06:51,595 --> 00:06:55,963
If we're cold or hungry, we won't be able to think straight or with any pleasure.

53
00:06:56,004 --> 00:07:08,007
It's only when we get a meal inside us and are tucked up in front of a warm fire that we'll feel like ourselves again, able to engage happily with our book or computer.

54
00:07:09,911 --> 00:07:12,557
So even if we don't take much pleasure...

55
00:07:13,836 --> 00:07:25,572
So even if we don't take much notice of sense pleasures, we're depending on them to let our minds pursue their cerebral pleasures and there inform that all-important sense of me.

56
00:07:26,934 --> 00:07:40,451
As such, we're at risk from the floods of sensuality whenever our basic needs for food and warmth are not met, when any of our senses fail or when our body is wracked with pain.

57
00:07:44,312 --> 00:07:52,305
The next flood, termed becoming, sweeps us away when we identify with our personal history and its projection into the future.

58
00:07:52,346 --> 00:08:01,802
It seems so obvious that we were the child we remember from our school days and that we will be the older person who will bear our name and passport tomorrow.

59
00:08:03,545 --> 00:08:08,632
In the steady gaze of a pāsana, this illusion can sometimes be seen through.

60
00:08:09,202 --> 00:08:17,216
We sense a mass of changing sensations, thoughts, moods, but no central control headquarters to call me.

61
00:08:19,579 --> 00:08:28,394
But the belief in ourselves as a personal identity has been taken for granted throughout our lives and forms the basis for almost all our thoughts.

62
00:08:29,596 --> 00:08:35,024
And so the illusion of self returns again and again, both on and off the cushion.

63
00:08:36,034 --> 00:08:40,682
We are then prey to floods of regret for the past as well as worry about the future.

64
00:08:40,702 --> 00:08:42,885
How will I get everything done?

65
00:08:43,727 --> 00:08:45,129
Will I succeed in my career?

66
00:08:46,072 --> 00:08:47,274
Will people respect me?

67
00:08:48,515 --> 00:08:49,496
Does anyone love me?

68
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:57,029
That's not to say we can ignore our personal history and its likely course in the future.

69
00:08:57,517 --> 00:09:08,467
Life is a precious opportunity for liberation and unless we look after the unenlightened person we appear to be just now, we won't be able to liberate that person from suffering.

70
00:09:10,070 --> 00:09:14,433
That can mean looking after our career, our good name, our family and so on.

71
00:09:15,754 --> 00:09:24,604
The raft formed from the Anatta perspective lets us do all this without worrying and obsessing over our future or regretting our past.

72
00:09:27,503 --> 00:09:31,110
Another flood comes when we attach to views and opinions.

73
00:09:32,774 --> 00:09:39,748
How many of us can have a completely calm, rational discussion about politics or religion, abortion or euthanasia?

74
00:09:41,471 --> 00:09:43,475
If we've no opinion, that makes it easy.

75
00:09:43,514 --> 00:09:49,427
But perhaps we've chosen non-committal as a way of avoiding hurt if our views were rejected.

76
00:09:50,538 --> 00:09:59,769
And even if we can ignore these somewhat abstract questions, we'll probably have a cherished opinion on how to hang wallpaper or how to cook the best Christmas pudding.

77
00:10:01,431 --> 00:10:09,441
So the flood can sweep us away when someone dismisses our opinions on these matters and we feel small, hurt and disrespected.

78
00:10:11,403 --> 00:10:16,950
Finally, and underlying all of these, we have the flood of ignorance.

79
00:10:19,174 --> 00:10:26,062
That term is often used insultingly, but here it means that we don't know how to make ourselves happy.

80
00:10:27,924 --> 00:10:31,769
Happiness comes when we live from the perspective of the Four Noble Truths.

81
00:10:33,051 --> 00:10:41,519
While ignorance means that we don't fully understand these, so we're looking for happiness in all the wrong places.

82
00:10:42,884 --> 00:10:47,708
We're assuming the next romance will make us happy or becoming a millionaire.

83
00:10:48,168 --> 00:10:49,090
That should do the trick.

84
00:10:50,471 --> 00:10:57,177
Basically, we get swept away by the first three floods because we're already drifting in the flood of ignorance.

85
00:11:00,221 --> 00:11:05,647
It's worth reminding ourselves that we don't have to know everything in order to be free from suffering.

86
00:11:06,988 --> 00:11:10,511
We only have to understand the four noble truths.

87
00:11:11,892 --> 00:11:16,998
We can be quite ignorant about biology, music and gardening and still be perfectly happy.

88
00:11:18,519 --> 00:11:23,206
We might not know the best way to organise people or the best decisions to make in our life.

89
00:11:24,748 --> 00:11:27,171
The Buddha's first sermon was a complete failure.

90
00:11:27,831 --> 00:11:32,937
The person walked away after the Buddha's attempt to describe his enlightened state.

91
00:11:36,951 --> 00:11:38,995
So the Buddha wasn't omniscient.

92
00:11:39,475 --> 00:11:40,677
He could make mistakes.

93
00:11:41,418 --> 00:11:43,580
He had to experiment and see what worked.

94
00:11:44,961 --> 00:11:51,971
The only mistake he could never make after enlightenment was to let desire cause suffering.

95
00:11:54,715 --> 00:11:59,341
Unlike the Buddha, here we are on our perilous shoreline.

96
00:12:00,923 --> 00:12:05,928
One moment it feels secure, the next it's collapsing like quicksand.

97
00:12:07,174 --> 00:12:09,116
The water in front of us is treacherous.

98
00:12:10,479 --> 00:12:14,984
But in the distance we see another shore that's stable and secure.

99
00:12:16,645 --> 00:12:20,009
This gives us the spark of faith we need to get started.

100
00:12:21,010 --> 00:12:24,495
It gets us looking around for materials that could make a raft.

101
00:12:26,717 --> 00:12:28,700
And to be honest, they don't look promising.

102
00:12:29,561 --> 00:12:32,845
Grass and twigs and branches and leaves.

103
00:12:32,993 --> 00:12:39,460
The grass I can only imagine is long reed-like stems that could be used to bind twigs and branches together.

104
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:43,403
Flimsy, makeshift, rickety fragile.

105
00:12:44,384 --> 00:12:47,187
That is the image the Buddha is giving us for our raft.

106
00:12:48,950 --> 00:12:51,091
It takes courage to set out at all.

107
00:12:51,131 --> 00:12:58,679
This means that we don't have to be experts before we start practising.

108
00:12:59,351 --> 00:13:04,398
We just use whatever bits of information or skill we have and get stuck in.

109
00:13:05,580 --> 00:13:07,782
And don't expect the ride to be easy.

110
00:13:08,663 --> 00:13:10,164
It's not a cruise ship we're on.

111
00:13:11,005 --> 00:13:12,707
It's a very flimsy raft.

112
00:13:13,909 --> 00:13:21,259
We're spread-eagled on it, just barely clear of the floodwaters, paddling through these using our hands and feet.

113
00:13:24,293 --> 00:13:34,326
I think this is a great image to console us for the very unedifying picture we get of ourselves as we scramble our Dharma practice together in the midst of a crisis.

114
00:13:38,052 --> 00:13:41,057
At times we'll probably lose sight of the far shore.

115
00:13:42,860 --> 00:13:50,210
To tell us whether we're still going the right direction, we have another water metaphor the Buddha gives for spiritual practice.

116
00:13:51,412 --> 00:13:52,714
Swimming upstream.

117
00:13:53,976 --> 00:14:00,486
We're always going against the current of the floods, against the habitual desires of our conditioning.

118
00:14:01,509 --> 00:14:04,953
Whatever we don't want to do, that's what we need to do.

119
00:14:06,476 --> 00:14:09,682
If we want to gobble our dinner, we need to slow down.

120
00:14:09,721 --> 00:14:16,272
If we want to sink into despair, that's when we need to find some reason to be hopeful.

121
00:14:17,533 --> 00:14:26,947
Even when we can't see where we're heading, we can detect the direction that desire is sweeping us and work against that strong current.

122
00:14:30,511 --> 00:14:32,293
Somehow we make it across.

123
00:14:33,836 --> 00:14:36,559
We're on that wonderful beach, safe and sound.

124
00:14:37,822 --> 00:14:39,845
Our little raft has done its job.

125
00:14:41,145 --> 00:14:43,068
We're naturally delighted with it.

126
00:14:44,246 --> 00:14:52,020
We might also be attached to it, thinking we might need it again, for who knows what the next shoreline will look like.

127
00:14:53,683 --> 00:15:02,759
And we might be justifiably proud of it and want it as a trophy, to show people how clever we were in getting across the stormy sea.

128
00:15:04,162 --> 00:15:08,769
So we're tempted to hoist it on our shoulder and take it with us on our journey.

129
00:15:10,623 --> 00:15:13,347
But according to the Buddha, this isn't wise.

130
00:15:14,649 --> 00:15:17,095
We're to leave our beloved raft behind.

131
00:15:17,154 --> 00:15:25,830
This tells us that we can't cling to any aspect of the Noble Eightfold Path.

132
00:15:26,096 --> 00:15:31,907
Just because we practiced right speech in a tricky situation, we shouldn't think of ourselves as experts.

133
00:15:33,009 --> 00:15:38,118
It is so tempting to think, okay, I've learned that lesson, I'll never make that mistake again.

134
00:15:38,177 --> 00:15:42,365
But then to our utter dismay, we fall back into the same trap.

135
00:15:43,846 --> 00:15:51,801
The conditioning that pulls us into the floods goes deep and we have to relearn the Dhamma, make a new raft in each new situation.

136
00:15:53,182 --> 00:16:03,474
But it's also fair to say that we get better at finding materials for our raft and more skilled in binding these together, more sensitive to the flow of the current.

137
00:16:04,754 --> 00:16:07,999
Also our muscles develop so we can paddle more vigorously.

138
00:16:09,159 --> 00:16:13,846
And we gain more and more confidence that we will, at some stage, make it to the other shore.

139
00:16:15,006 --> 00:16:18,530
So we're willing to venture out in ever more skimpy rafts.

140
00:16:20,047 --> 00:16:21,688
Let's look at a practical example.

141
00:16:22,870 --> 00:16:26,514
Suppose you had a really rough morning's meditation here at Satipaña.

142
00:16:27,394 --> 00:16:30,639
You've lost any confidence you ever had regarding meditation.

143
00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:33,802
All morning your mind kept wandering.

144
00:16:34,743 --> 00:16:37,927
By the 11 a.m. meditation you were totally fed up.

145
00:16:39,028 --> 00:16:45,615
Again and again you woke up to find yourself in the middle of a long moan about how hopeless things are.

146
00:16:46,945 --> 00:16:51,527
When the bell goes for lunch, you just want to gobble it all up and dive into bed for an hour.

147
00:16:53,134 --> 00:16:54,542
What floods are at work here?

148
00:16:55,653 --> 00:16:58,615
We're unhappy and don't know how to make ourselves happy.

149
00:16:59,736 --> 00:17:02,119
That summarises our basic problem in life.

150
00:17:02,940 --> 00:17:07,503
Unhappiness at base stems from not understanding the Four Noble Truths.

151
00:17:08,704 --> 00:17:10,846
So we're adrift in the flood of ignorance.

152
00:17:12,048 --> 00:17:14,329
Lunch and bed represent sense pleasures.

153
00:17:15,211 --> 00:17:19,473
So the flood of sensuality is flowing over the flood of ignorance.

154
00:17:19,493 --> 00:17:25,660
And with a bit of luck, the pleasures of food and being stretched out on a warm bed will let us forget our troubles for a while.

155
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:29,105
But at what cost do we enter this flood?

156
00:17:30,767 --> 00:17:34,011
One episode of laziness might not do too much harm.

157
00:17:34,711 --> 00:17:40,980
But the trouble is that the next time you're feeling low, you'll want to gobble your lunch twice as fast and sleep for twice as long.

158
00:17:41,682 --> 00:17:45,827
If this goes on, then pretty soon you won't return for the afternoon shift at all.

159
00:17:46,749 --> 00:17:49,673
And then you'll feel even more rotten and depressed.

160
00:17:51,086 --> 00:17:58,316
Basically, the current starts off gently, but pulls us into ever faster currents that sweep us further and further from the shore.

161
00:18:00,699 --> 00:18:03,823
So where can we find materials for our raft?

162
00:18:04,704 --> 00:18:07,107
First and foremost, we have mindfulness.

163
00:18:08,269 --> 00:18:10,652
We can acknowledge that we're fed up and miserable.

164
00:18:11,573 --> 00:18:15,157
Sounds easy, but the temptation to ignore our moods can be strong.

165
00:18:16,179 --> 00:18:20,605
We need a steady practice to work mindfully with bad moods such as this.

166
00:18:22,255 --> 00:18:28,201
To start making a raft, you could resolve to spend a few minutes in mindful acknowledgement of the bad mood.

167
00:18:29,102 --> 00:18:37,109
In theory, this is what you've been doing all morning, but sometimes we lose sight of the broader picture in our effort to still the mind in meditation.

168
00:18:37,170 --> 00:18:49,663
As we relax when the bell goes, and as we're walking toward the lunchroom, that broader awareness might actually be the first real acknowledgement of how low your mood has descended.

169
00:18:50,673 --> 00:19:00,584
Acknowledging the bad humour changes the situation radically and with this broader awareness it is worth re-entering the gaze of a pasana for another few minutes.

170
00:19:04,028 --> 00:19:13,557
You could do this while sitting at table after serving yourself your dinner, noting the mood and feeling the bodily sensations associated with it.

171
00:19:15,226 --> 00:19:17,450
Even one minute will make a huge difference.

172
00:19:18,391 --> 00:19:25,102
Although you might still feel low, you will feel much better for having taken the time and trouble to acknowledge the mood mindfully.

173
00:19:26,084 --> 00:19:31,393
You might even make it all the way to the far shore and feel hopeful about your meditation practice again.

174
00:19:33,236 --> 00:19:36,121
Vipassana practice will always make a really good raft.

175
00:19:37,682 --> 00:19:40,508
But suppose you can't muster the energy for this.

176
00:19:40,993 --> 00:19:48,163
Just like it was doing all morning, your mind gets sucked into negative thoughts the moment you decide to do a minute's practice at the dining room table.

177
00:19:49,545 --> 00:19:58,017
Instead of a pasana, you could choose mindful eating as the framework for your raft, noting all the physical sensations.

178
00:20:00,019 --> 00:20:03,002
For extra buoyancy, you could pick up some metta.

179
00:20:04,806 --> 00:20:07,930
You could wish yourself well as you cut up a potato.

180
00:20:08,585 --> 00:20:11,950
As you're chewing this, you can wish that the meal will cheer you up.

181
00:20:13,551 --> 00:20:22,685
If your mood lightens, you could add in mudita, appreciating the meal and congratulating yourself for having looked after yourself well in a tricky situation.

182
00:20:23,948 --> 00:20:30,136
Now suppose wishing ourselves well seems forced and contrived and puts us in even worse humour.

183
00:20:31,467 --> 00:20:38,778
In that case, compassion could be more appropriate, starting off by acknowledging that we're having a really bad time.

184
00:20:40,240 --> 00:20:45,268
It often helps to express sympathy with a gesture, perhaps a hand on the heart.

185
00:20:46,410 --> 00:20:55,523
The phrase, may I be free from suffering, or may I be free from anger and ill will, could feel more congruent than meta good wishes.

186
00:20:57,166 --> 00:20:59,871
This is to work very tenderly with ourselves.

187
00:21:01,031 --> 00:21:11,124
If we can also be patient, not expecting ourselves to cheer up anytime soon, we can be assured that this is a very genuine part of our spiritual practice.

188
00:21:14,367 --> 00:21:27,765
But if it's one of those times when we're too low or fed up for self-compassion, we could try to pick up some equanimity for our raft with a phrase like, may I not make things worse for myself?

189
00:21:29,787 --> 00:21:34,473
If that stems the flow of negativity for a moment, we could add some other bits of wisdom.

190
00:21:35,115 --> 00:21:39,682
A phrase like, this too will pass, reminds us of Anicca.

191
00:21:42,125 --> 00:21:47,854
No matter how we decide to work with bad humour, we've avoided the temptation to gobble and dive into bed.

192
00:21:48,596 --> 00:21:51,058
So we're buoying up our raft with renunciation.

193
00:21:52,721 --> 00:21:58,730
When the Buddha first thought of a life of renunciation, he noticed, my heart did not leap up with joy.

194
00:21:59,842 --> 00:22:04,769
We find it much easier to be enthusiastic about meta, compassion, mindfulness etc.

195
00:22:05,210 --> 00:22:06,191
than renunciation.

196
00:22:07,512 --> 00:22:13,761
Deferring pleasure isn't easy, especially as we've no control over when and if any rewards will come through.

197
00:22:16,566 --> 00:22:24,718
But I'm sure you'll agree that you would feel immeasurably better for having worked mindfully with a bad humour than if you'd given in to all its demands.

198
00:22:25,204 --> 00:22:31,836
Although the thought of renunciation doesn't make our hearts leap with joy, the practice of it brings a freedom.

199
00:22:32,998 --> 00:22:36,384
We realise we don't have to be controlled by our moods or obsessions.

200
00:22:37,306 --> 00:22:39,288
Such a relief.

201
00:22:39,308 --> 00:22:40,951
A soup song of Nibbana.

202
00:22:43,278 --> 00:22:53,230
But if the flood of sensuality sweeps us off our feet and we're already gobbling our dinner, we could try making a supreme effort and note, indulging, indulging.

203
00:22:54,152 --> 00:22:56,394
Can we feel any of the pleasure this is giving?

204
00:22:57,355 --> 00:23:00,038
If so, can we focus on this as we eat?

205
00:23:00,900 --> 00:23:03,042
You could call it mindful gobbling.

206
00:23:04,003 --> 00:23:10,972
A rickety raft for sure, but if it keeps us present, it's doing its job.

207
00:23:12,521 --> 00:23:19,314
It's also possible that when we note indulging, indulging, we are immediately recaptured by our negativity.

208
00:23:20,476 --> 00:23:25,684
We remember our bad humour and now there might be a good dollop of shame added to this as well.

209
00:23:26,967 --> 00:23:30,534
Shame can be used skilfully because it tells us we're going astray.

210
00:23:30,554 --> 00:23:35,221
We've been reacting, indulging in food as a means of escape.

211
00:23:37,057 --> 00:23:46,680
Although we might feel even worse after noting indulgence, that very discomfort can prompt us to look around for a few materials to start making a raft.

212
00:23:48,482 --> 00:23:50,205
It's never too late to start.

213
00:23:51,267 --> 00:24:02,284
Even if we're on the last bite, any of the options suggested above are still available, though we might now have to start with self-forgiveness and the resolve that we can mend our ways.

214
00:24:03,385 --> 00:24:08,974
These are the times that it really helps to remember the image of being spread-eagled on a rickety raft.

215
00:24:09,955 --> 00:24:12,921
We don't have to look good to practice the Dhamma.

216
00:24:15,549 --> 00:24:31,015
In fact, the shame of knowing we've been acting unskilfully is always a good place to start building a raft.

217
00:24:32,196 --> 00:24:35,102
I know one man who had earlier in life suffered from alcoholism.

218
00:24:35,903 --> 00:24:41,592
After one bad bout he was nursing a hangover and sitting in the kitchen feeling really miserable.

219
00:24:42,044 --> 00:24:46,849
He was watching his wife doing some housework, too sick and depressed to offer any help.

220
00:24:47,971 --> 00:24:51,835
As she passed him by, she gave him a look of total disgust.

221
00:24:52,736 --> 00:24:57,101
He had the thought, you're right, I am a louse, but I can do better.

222
00:24:57,141 --> 00:25:08,894
He gave up drinking completely from that moment, went on to form and run a very successful business, and when I met him years later, he was a regular, he was a regular,

223
00:25:11,525 --> 00:25:15,851
And when I met him years later, he was regularly going to 10-day Vipassana retreats.

224
00:25:19,096 --> 00:25:24,364
When we register guilt or shame mindfully, they can stir us to find a way to mend our ways.

225
00:25:25,665 --> 00:25:36,182
No matter how many break periods we've wasted gobbling and snoring, we can choose the thought, I can do better than this, and make faith the first component of our raft.

226
00:25:38,660 --> 00:25:42,746
Let's now look at a practical example of the flood of views.

227
00:25:45,470 --> 00:25:49,355
Suppose we've got ourselves into a heated debate about the refugee crisis.

228
00:25:50,657 --> 00:25:57,468
Our adversary is fiercely arguing for border closures while we are stoutly defending the refugees' rights to asylum.

229
00:25:58,628 --> 00:26:01,713
We're feeling threatened by the situation and getting agitated.

230
00:26:03,247 --> 00:26:04,788
It's a complex situation.

231
00:26:05,671 --> 00:26:11,319
On the one hand, we're expressing compassion for refugees, so we're developing one of the Brahma Vihara.

232
00:26:12,201 --> 00:26:14,805
On the other hand, we're in danger of ill will.

233
00:26:16,988 --> 00:26:20,614
Mindfulness would be the main material to frame our raft.

234
00:26:21,421 --> 00:26:31,178
Unless we're aware of the anger rising within us, we could easily snap at our opponent, insult them, scorn their lack of compassion or taunt them with sarcastic comments.

235
00:26:32,359 --> 00:26:42,416
If we're a clever debater, we could find ways to ridicule their arguments and belittle them, unconscious of the irony that we're using cruel words to argue for compassion.

236
00:26:45,619 --> 00:26:49,644
If we're not good at debate, we could find ourselves on the receiving end of cruelty.

237
00:26:49,664 --> 00:26:59,036
If we take their scorn to heart and let it wreck our confidence, we might end up sowing seeds of enmity, unable to think well of that person again.

238
00:26:59,096 --> 00:27:09,028
We'll have been carried far away by the floods without any awareness of this, insisting that we're doing the right thing, standing up for the rights of refugees.

239
00:27:11,252 --> 00:27:16,159
With mindfulness, we'll feel and acknowledge anger and be aware of the floods threatening us.

240
00:27:17,440 --> 00:27:24,989
Once we have the frame of mindfulness in place, the most useful material for this particular raft would be right speech.

241
00:27:26,369 --> 00:27:28,172
Here's the definition the Buddha gives.

242
00:27:29,673 --> 00:27:30,875
And what is right speech?

243
00:27:31,675 --> 00:27:38,644
Abstaining from lying, from divisive speech, from abusive speech, and from idle chatter.

244
00:27:39,298 --> 00:27:41,122
This is called right speech.

245
00:27:43,085 --> 00:27:45,367
In another teaching he puts it in positive terms.

246
00:27:46,690 --> 00:27:48,373
It is spoken at the right time.

247
00:27:49,294 --> 00:27:50,536
It is spoken in truth.

248
00:27:51,518 --> 00:27:53,200
It is spoken affectionately.

249
00:27:54,241 --> 00:27:55,923
It is spoken beneficially.

250
00:27:56,986 --> 00:27:59,028
It is spoken with a mind of

251
00:28:02,619 --> 00:28:08,646
We're not likely to be able to sift every word through the Buddha's filters while we're in the middle of a heated argument.

252
00:28:09,587 --> 00:28:21,261
But the more often we reflect on these lists and let them influence our speech in less conflicting situations, the more easily we'll be able to attach right speech to our raft when we really need it.

253
00:28:23,664 --> 00:28:30,113
So let's see how our communication is measuring up to the Buddha's standards in this particular situation.

254
00:28:31,055 --> 00:28:33,417
We're certainly not engaged in idle chatter.

255
00:28:34,278 --> 00:28:38,223
Our intention is beneficial and we're not using divisive speech.

256
00:28:39,164 --> 00:28:40,205
So far so good.

257
00:28:41,166 --> 00:28:48,415
Hopefully also we're being truthful, though this will be compromised if we're exaggerating facts and figures to score our point.

258
00:28:51,078 --> 00:28:56,184
Another consideration, according to the Buddha, is whether our speech is timely.

259
00:28:56,417 --> 00:29:01,824
If we can see that our adversary is completely closed to our point of view, then our words are a waste of time.

260
00:29:02,744 --> 00:29:09,832
All we're doing is letting that person sow their own seeds of hatred, as well as putting ourselves in danger of the flood of views.

261
00:29:11,012 --> 00:29:14,896
Out of compassion for self and other, we should put an end to the argument.

262
00:29:17,319 --> 00:29:24,146
We also need to ask ourselves whether we're speaking with a mind of goodwill, and whether our words are gentle or harsh.

263
00:29:25,307 --> 00:29:26,710
These are obviously related.

264
00:29:27,830 --> 00:29:33,637
If we're speaking with goodwill, we won't be shouting or letting sarcastic or insulting remarks slip out.

265
00:29:34,920 --> 00:29:41,028
At times we might believe we're speaking with goodwill, unaware of how anger has escalated in the heat of the moment.

266
00:29:42,650 --> 00:29:50,859
If we hear ourselves using harsh words or a scornful tone, we have the feedback we need to acknowledge that anger is getting the better of us.

267
00:29:52,038 --> 00:29:56,542
In that case, we have to scrabble around to find a way of binding the raft together again.

268
00:29:58,326 --> 00:30:00,689
One of the Brahma-Vihara might do the trick.

269
00:30:01,809 --> 00:30:09,980
Equanimity is often the most practical place to start, with a wish such as, may I not do harm on account of my anger.

270
00:30:11,141 --> 00:30:15,066
If that steadies the raft, you could add a dash of metta, for example.

271
00:30:16,047 --> 00:30:19,951
May this conversation be beneficial to us both.

272
00:30:23,054 --> 00:30:27,801
It's tough work though, trying to bind a rickety raft together on stormy waters.

273
00:30:29,144 --> 00:30:33,352
So should we withdraw from the conversation as soon as we feel anger rising?

274
00:30:35,936 --> 00:30:42,268
That depends on how well we can trust ourselves to work with anger in a conflict such as this.

275
00:30:44,191 --> 00:30:47,998
If we're mindful of anger, we're not being controlled by it.

276
00:30:49,295 --> 00:30:54,844
We can feel angry but maintain an attitude of no harm or even of goodwill.

277
00:30:56,686 --> 00:31:01,513
This is the great benefit of working with the difficult person in our metta practice.

278
00:31:02,895 --> 00:31:13,092
So long as we can maintain the no harm attitude, we can safely continue to argue our case no matter what fury might be firing through our veins.

279
00:31:15,788 --> 00:31:19,913
In fact, engaging with the argument will be an excellent spiritual practice.

280
00:31:21,034 --> 00:31:29,986
We're mindfully watching anger and letting it transform into compassion, which is hard enough to do on the cushion, never mind in a social situation.

281
00:31:31,708 --> 00:31:39,738
If we can somehow make it to the other shore, we should give ourselves a major sadhu for steering our raft through such a flood.

282
00:31:42,500 --> 00:31:43,382
Mindfulness

283
00:31:45,016 --> 00:31:50,361
are the primary materials we need when the flood of views threatens.

284
00:31:52,643 --> 00:31:57,186
It can also help to remember the Buddha's usual method of engaging people in debate.

285
00:31:59,449 --> 00:32:08,477
He would listen to their views carefully and then question them, drawing them out so that they eventually saw the weakness in their argument.

286
00:32:10,219 --> 00:32:12,441
Only then would he give his own view.

287
00:32:13,686 --> 00:32:20,417
If we could use this model, we would be doing a lot more listening than we usually do during a heated argument.

288
00:32:21,740 --> 00:32:27,388
This will also help keep us calm and give us a much better chance of controlling any anger.

289
00:32:29,692 --> 00:32:37,904
In order to ask useful questions, we will have to consider their point of view seriously, which in itself is an act of metta.

290
00:32:41,462 --> 00:32:44,950
You might rarely get into controversial discussions like this.

291
00:32:46,511 --> 00:32:50,058
Perhaps you don't have strong views on any matters, on many matters.

292
00:32:52,403 --> 00:32:57,292
Those of us in this category might therefore think that at least we're free from the flood of views.

293
00:32:59,416 --> 00:33:03,825
But if someone bullies us, it's hard to resist the view that they are horrid and cruel.

294
00:33:05,205 --> 00:33:14,836
Or if our partner repeatedly admits to do their share of housework, we'd probably be rehashing thoughts like, he's so mean and lazy, or she's so thoughtless.

295
00:33:16,377 --> 00:33:23,806
These views can bind us, and so we might never appreciate how much attention our partner pays to the children, for example.

296
00:33:25,567 --> 00:33:34,317
If we're sharing responsibility for a project, it's easy to get into arguments about how things ought to be done, convinced that our view is right.

297
00:33:36,931 --> 00:33:43,038
Even if we don't have strong political or religious views, we have opinions on almost everything we do.

298
00:33:43,078 --> 00:33:48,165
And if someone agrees with these, we'll feel angry, hurt or threatened.

299
00:33:49,188 --> 00:33:53,794
Thus all of us, even the meek and mild, are at risk from the flood of views.

300
00:33:56,698 --> 00:33:59,461
You can explore this flood here on Retreat.

301
00:34:00,319 --> 00:34:11,016
Even though we're not talking out loud, how many arguments do we have in our heads, insisting over and over again how right we are and how wrong our imaginary adversary is?

302
00:34:12,297 --> 00:34:15,061
To make a raft, we use body awareness.

303
00:34:16,224 --> 00:34:22,193
Feeling the sensations generated by all those strident thoughts, we paddle our way through the flood.

304
00:34:23,050 --> 00:34:31,201
The far shore might come into view as a thought like, what does it really matter who's right or wrong, slips through the turmoil.

305
00:34:33,623 --> 00:34:44,298
The more often we negotiate our way through this flood in Vipassana, the more easily we make a raft when the tsunami comes our way in a heated conversation during daily life.

306
00:34:45,916 --> 00:34:56,257
Another very good practice to prepare us for this flood is to reflect on the Buddha's list for right speech and asking ourselves whether we often transgress these unwittingly.

307
00:34:56,277 --> 00:35:02,271
Idle or untimely speech would be a danger for many of us.

308
00:35:03,483 --> 00:35:07,268
This doesn't mean we should only speak when we have something really important to say.

309
00:35:07,329 --> 00:35:11,356
The Buddha was always happy to exchange pleasantries.

310
00:35:12,257 --> 00:35:16,503
These are just a socially acceptable way of saying, may you be well and happy.

311
00:35:18,226 --> 00:35:21,472
So they are a metta practice and to be cherished.

312
00:35:22,632 --> 00:35:28,663
But conversations easily fall into moaning about our woes or giving out about third parties.

313
00:35:29,503 --> 00:35:32,728
In that case, we're being swept away by the flood of views.

314
00:35:33,949 --> 00:35:41,199
Our moans reflect the view that the world should not have done this to me or that the third party should have behaved differently.

315
00:35:43,262 --> 00:35:53,275
For example, the car broke down and I had to get it towed away, cost me £300 and then my boss decides to dock me an hour's pay for being late.

316
00:35:55,197 --> 00:35:58,583
If that's said mindfully, as a factual statement,

317
00:35:59,068 --> 00:36:03,195
or with clarity in our distress and need for sympathy, then no problem.

318
00:36:04,097 --> 00:36:06,320
We need to be able to tell others our bad news.

319
00:36:07,123 --> 00:36:10,989
It's part of the way we help each other to deal with the truth of dukkha.

320
00:36:12,331 --> 00:36:25,313
But if we're spitting the words out in anger and injecting swear words about our boss and the car, then we're caught in the flood, proclaiming our view of how rotten the world is and especially our rotten car and boss.

321
00:36:26,304 --> 00:36:32,311
We're not so much looking for sympathy, more interested in having our view of the rotten world confirmed.

322
00:36:34,434 --> 00:36:38,858
Suppose we've spat out that much and then suddenly remember our Dhamma practice.

323
00:36:39,800 --> 00:36:42,382
We need to start building a raft pronto.

324
00:36:44,365 --> 00:36:47,929
Mindfulness would be the best start, acknowledging anger.

325
00:36:49,311 --> 00:36:56,059
We then need to acknowledge this to whoever we've been talking to and apologize for having dumped our bad temper on them.

326
00:36:57,119 --> 00:36:59,061
This would be an example of right speech.

327
00:37:00,123 --> 00:37:02,766
The anger relieves some of the burden we've placed on them.

328
00:37:03,867 --> 00:37:05,389
So it is beneficial speech.

329
00:37:06,992 --> 00:37:14,503
All of this might have calmed us enough for some self-compassion, acknowledging in a sympathetic way how rotten we feel.

330
00:37:14,543 --> 00:37:26,298
Equanimity-style good wishes such as, may I take care of myself wisely, would help us bear the burden until our anger dissipates.

331
00:37:27,916 --> 00:37:38,952
In general, right speech is an important aspect of any raft to take us across the flood of views, as this flood will be at its swiftest when we're expressing our views to another person.

332
00:37:40,956 --> 00:37:51,713
The more often we take care to practice right speech in simple situations when we're not threatened by the flood, the easier it will be for us to build our raft when we need it.

333
00:37:55,135 --> 00:38:01,442
We'll continue with this teaching on the raft tomorrow night and give some examples of working with the other floods.

334
00:38:02,684 --> 00:38:13,876
For the moment, let's remind ourselves that we don't have to despair when we find ourselves in a tantrum and acting as if we'd never done a moment's mindfulness practice in our lives.

335
00:38:15,338 --> 00:38:21,744
The moment we see our tantrum is the moment to start looking around for any branches or twigs that could make a raft.

336
00:38:22,887 --> 00:38:24,889
It's never too late to start.

337
00:38:25,847 --> 00:38:32,418
The present moment never condemns us or shuts us out from its infinite store of wisdom and compassion.

338
00:38:35,583 --> 00:38:43,755
May this reflection help us build and trust our rickety rafts and paddle them swiftly to the far shores.

